<HL>
   Victoria's Secret?
   Keep Earnings Up
   With Garter Belts
   ---
   Racy Catalog Is Controversial,
   Popular, and Showing Up
   In Very Unlikely Places
   ----
   By James S. Hirsch
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/29/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<CO>
   LTD
</CO>
<IN>
SPECIALTY APPAREL RETAILERS (SAP)
ADVERTISING, MARKETING, PUBLIC RELATIONS (ADV)
</IN>
<LP>
   Victoria's Secret catalog, the one with the attractive
models wearing tiny little underthings that cost a fortune
per square inch, is surfacing in the most unlikely places.
   Like at Popkin &amp; Stern, a large St. Louis law firm.
Attorney Jeff Michelman once asked his secretary to send a
local publisher a copy of Insight, a sober magazine of
politics and opinion, along with a note about an article on
free speech. Then he left the magazine on his desk. Big
mistake. Also on his desk lay a Victoria's Secret catalog,
which -- you guessed it -- the secretary mailed instead.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The puzzled publisher called Mr. Michelman to ask what,
exactly, was the relationship between lingerie and free
speech. "I went through the color spectrum from pale to red
and back to pale again," Mr. Michelman says.
   Which doesn't explain, of course, what a Victoria's Secret
catalog was doing on Mr. Michelman's mahogany desk to begin
with. But that's the point: The glossy catalog of see-through
lace camisoles, floral garter belts and sheer teddies now can
be found in boardrooms as well as bedrooms, on desk tops as
well as coffee tables -- and in Richard Emory's briefcase.
Says Mr. Emory, a St. Louis real-estate investor: "It takes
the edge off an otherwise difficult day. It's sort of like a
martini on paper."
   As a result, the controversial catalog that pioneered sexy
underwear as fashion has become one of the fastest growing
mail-order businesses. It now offers a lot more than garter
belts, G-strings and sexy poses, but it's clear what makes a
lot of people pick it up. "I usually browse through it right
when I open the mailbox, and leave the bills," says Thomas
Buell of Dallas. And he's an actuary.
   You can find Mr. Buell's catalog on the coffee table along
with his sports magazines. But to him, it's more than just a
display piece. Last year, Mr. Buell ordered a pair of silk
boxer shorts with geese and ducks for $40. With his willpower
weakened, he then visited a Victoria's Secret store and
bought $300 more worth of briefs. After all, the paisley went
with his sheets and comforter. "It's going to take me a year
to pay off my underwear," he says glumly.
   The company, which is a division of Limited Inc., won't
disclose numbers, but it says sales and earnings doubled last
year. Analysts estimate sales have increased to $120 million
from under $30 million four years ago. As anyone who's on the
mailing list can attest, there seems to be a new catalog
every week -- actually there are about 15 a year -- but the
company won't say how many millions are delivered.
   Among the catalogs for popcorn, hunting gear, chocolate
and thimbles, it's easy to see why Victoria's Secret stands
out. "When you get Lands' End, what are you going to do,
fantasize that you're fishing?" asks Victoria Brown, a Wall
Street analyst and portfolio manager.
   To hear the company talk about it, the catalog has
liberated generations of repressed pajama wearers. "It's been
a process of educating the entire population that lingerie
can be fun, sensuous, fashionable, and that it doesn't have
to be purely functional," says Cynthia Fedus, president of
Victoria's Secret Catalogue. "We're selling hope."
   The company also has 500 stores, all in the U.S. Two
hundred have opened in the past two years, and another 75 are
scheduled for this year. But the catalog, which operates
independent of the stores, is still critical, and Gregg Young
can tell you one reason why. Mr. Young once went into a
Victoria's Secret store to buy some underwear for his
girlfriend. He nervously selected a pair of black satin
panties. Then, unfortunately, he was forced to follow the
saleswoman around the store while she looked for the matching
garter belt and bra.
   "I was the only guy in the store," says Mr. Young, who
swears the search for the garter belt took more than 30
minutes. "I almost fainted."
   Now, Mr. Young shops in the catalog -- so far, spending
about $800 on frilly garments.
   Women still account for most sales, but the company is
plying more and more men, including those on Wall Street.
Limited makes sure analysts are kept up to date on the latest
frills. When company executives brief analysts, "the first
thing they do is ask if we want to see the new catalog," says
Barry Bryant, an analyst at Prudential-Bache Securities. He
in turn stocks up on back issues in a file discreetly labeled
"Limited Miscellaneous." Mr. Bryant explains: "I use them as
an inducement for traders and salesmen to come into my
office."
   It took a while for the catalog to gain such a mainstream
following. Founded in 1977 in San Francisco, the business was
initially several low-brow lingerie stores and a tacky
mail-order catalog. The name poked fun at the Victorians'
outward prudishness.
   Leslie Wexner, Limited's chairman, bought the business in
1982 in a stock transaction valued at $1 million. The stores
were remodeled into potpourri-scented boutiques, with
spaghetti straps perfectly aligned and panties always
plumped.
   Meanwhile, the catalog limped along. It had more flesh
than fabric, picturing near-naked men and women groping for
each other in tawdry bedroom scenes. The publication
generated a storm of angry letters and calls.
   So the book was overhauled two years ago. To damp its
prurient reputation and appeal to a wider audience, the
catalog has been given a mannered, aristocratic look and is
filled with British affectations. The catalog price is listed
in pounds (two) as well as dollars (three), although it's
usually mailed for free. The word "pajamas" is spelled
"pyjamas," and men in boxer shorts read the Financial Times.
If you call the 800 number to place an order, the voice on
the answering machine speaks with a British accent.
   The catalog also tries to entice with some breathless
text. "Victoria's Secret satin and lace lingerie sets evening
alight. . . . Beginning the day with beautiful, unusual
lingerie can change her entire outlook."
   The catalog's sexy sleepwear and underwear ("a rich design
of peacock satin with black lace overlay creates the beauty
of the demi-bra and bikini") constitutes about half the
publication. There's a growing line of sportswear and evening
wear, and last year the company added toiletries, fragrances
and the boxer shorts. Men and women are no longer
photographed together. Complaints have slowed down.
   But they haven't stopped. Critics assert that dressing up
models in skimpy lingerie, amid the accouterments of a
luxurious boudoir, is simply exploitation with the veneer of
Victorian respectability.
   "Women are posed in postures of submission, and they're on
display," says Norma Ramos, general counsel for Women Against
Pornography, a New York-based advocacy group. Ms. Ramos says
the catalog is similar to ads for blue jeans, cars and other
products that use women's bodies to sell products. "Women get
the message that they should be sexually available," she
says.
   The company disputes that, but acknowledges that it does
strive to shock. "We've always had a certain segment of the
population that find both the store and the catalog
offensive," says Howard Gross, chief executive officer and
president of Victoria's Secret Stores. "But to be honest, if
we don't get some complaints we feel we aren't doing our
job."
   Despite the controversy, the catalog and the stores have
influenced how lingerie is marketed. Department stores used
to primarily sell low-margin "foundations" (bras and
girdles), and Frederick's of Hollywood offered naughty
nightwear.
   Today, big stores like Bloomingdale's run full-page
underwear ads of women in seductive poses and offer a richer
variety of frilly sleepwear. Frederick's, meanwhile, has
become more conservative, and its catalog is now a
less-upscale version of Victoria's Secret.
   Says Richard Grunsten, president of GSP Marketing Service
in Chicago, which produces catalogs: "Victoria's Secret
legitimized lingerie as something that's not kinky, but
something that's legitimate apparel."
   Well, maybe. A high-school theology teacher in Houston and
her husband, a prominent lawyer, hide their catalog when
guests arrive, and leave the National Geographic and Parent
magazines on the coffee table. The teacher asks -- insists,
actually -- that she not be identified. "If you're doing a
story on the Smithsonian magazine, you can use my name," she
says, "but not about this."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900529-0121
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900529-0121.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   LEISURE &amp; ARTS -- Bookshelf:
   New Look at a Man of Letters
   ----
   By Richard Locke
</HL>
<DATE>
05/29/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A21
</SO>
<LP>
   In Centennial Park in Nashville, Tenn., "The Athens of the
South," there's a full-sized, concrete replica of the
Parthenon, and up there on the pediment with all the other
deities sits a statue of Ganymede, the cupbearer of the gods.
The model for this Ganymede of 1922 was eight-year-old
Randall Jarrell, who so charmingly lectured the sculptors
about Greek myths that they asked to adopt him ("I would have
gone like that") and who eventually became one of the great
American men of letters of this century. Poet, critic,
novelist, editor, translator, teacher, children's book
writer, the creator of 27 books in a 25-year career, Jarrell
is the often ebullient subject of this new life and works by
William H. Pritchard (Farrar, Straus &amp; Giroux, 338 pages,
$25), himself a distinguished critic and biographer of Robert
Frost and other modern poets.
   Jarrell "always seemed more alive than other people, as if
constantly tuned up to the concert pitch that most people,
including poets, can maintain only for short and fortunate
stretches," wrote the poet Elizabeth Bishop, one of the fond
and sometimes exasperated circle of his friends that included
Robert Lowell, John Berryman, Hannah Arendt, Peter Taylor,
Adrienne Rich and a dozen other cultural gods and goddesses.
Enfant terrible and wit, Jarrell was bedazzling, merry,
intimidating, difficult, cruel, inspiring, incomparably
generous. And if we can't speak of an Age of Jarrell, as we
might speak of an Age of Lowell (meaning the dark, tormented,
rich midcentury decades), we can't forget that it was Randall
Jarrell who discovered the American genius of Whitman and
Frost and wrote inimitably of Lowell and Bishop and Marianne
Moore and William Carlos Williams. He was famous for his
wisecracks and terrifying one-liners, but (as Lowell said)
praise "was the glory of Randall's criticism."
</LP>
<TEXT>
   With all great men and women of letters, right or wrong
judgments matter less than how they get to them: We read
Jarrell for the writing, not the final verdicts, for his
articulation of a way of being in the world. His
unsystematic, unacademic, colloquial style epitomizes the
energy and delight of America discovering itself and European
culture right after World War II. Although today Jarrell's
reviews and articles may seem too journalistic and
philosophically naive to some, it's Mr. Pritchard's argument
that Jarrell is seriously misprized and misread as both a
critic and poet.
   His student years at Vanderbilt were spent with mentors
such as John Crowe Ransom, Allen Tate and Robert Penn Warren
(the conservative Southern Agrarians and Fugitives of the
30s, the New Critics of the 40s), but Jarrell (a "radical
liberal") ducked politics and ideological and scholastic
controversy. His criticism was undogmatically aesthetic and
unmoralistically moral. He was a literary writer in love with
adjectives and metaphors: His prose transcends its occasions
and takes on a gleeful creative life of its own that embodies
his belief that precise, enthusiastic reading and responding
could create a true American civilization. With what he
called "a sad heart at the supermarket," he was no populist
but a cultural democrat. The following lines from his 1950
essay "The Obscurity of the Poet" in his greatest book
"Poetry and the Age" (available from the Ecco Press) have a
new vitality in the era of Vaclav Havel:
   "Art matters not merely because it is the most magnificent
ornament and the most nearly unfailing occupation of our
lives, but because it is life itself. From Christ to Freud we
have believed that, if we know the truth, the truth will set
us free: art is indispensable because so much of this truth
can be learned through works of art and through works of art
alone . . . And all these things, by their very nature,
demand to be shared; if we are satisfied to know these things
ourselves, and to look with superiority or indifference at
those who do not have that knowledge, we have made a refusal
that corrupts us as surely as anything can. . . . One of the
oldest, deepest, and most nearly conclusive attractions of
democracy is manifested in our feeling that through it not
only material but also spiritual goods can be shared: that in
a democracy bread and justice, education and art, will be
accessible to everybody."
   Mr. Pritchard guides us through Jarrell's youth in
Nashville and Southern California; his years at Kenyon
College in Ohio where he lived with Lowell and Peter Taylor
and was "instructor in English and Director of Tennis"; his 3
1/2 years in the Army Air Corps training navigators and
working toward some of his strong war poems; his nearly 20
happy years teaching at a Southern women's college in
Greensboro, N.C.; his two marriages; his extraordinary
friendships; and his appetite for sports cars, cats, Chekhov,
John Kennedy, Donatello, Mahler, pro football (especially
Johnny Unitas), Balanchine and the Brothers Grimm.
   Jarrell suffered a nervous breakdown in his last years,
made a suicide attempt at 51, then recovered his health but
died in a still-controversial car accident (which Mr.
Pritchard believes was not a suicide) in October 1965.
   Mr. Pritchard's fine biography and its companion volume,
his "Randall Jarrell: Selected Poems" (Farrar, Straus &amp;
Giroux, 115 pages, $17.95) -- presenting 50 of Jarrell's 290
poems from 1941 through 1964, including several from his
great last collection, "The Lost World," published a few
months before he died -- afford us an opportunity to approach
this remarkable literary figure and his world anew.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900529-0120
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900529-0120.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   U.S. Trade Deficit Shrank
   During the First Quarter
</HL>
<DATE>
05/29/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2
</SO>
<IN>
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
ECONOMIC AND MONETARY INDICATORS (EMI)
ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)
</IN>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The U.S. merchandise trade deficit shrank to
$26.37 billion in the first quarter, on a balance-of-payments
basis, the smallest gap since the fourth quarter of 1983, the
Commerce Department reported.
   Both exports and imports set records. The department said
exports grew 4.7%, to $96.04 billion, while imports, boosted
by the highest volume of oil in more than 12 years, rose 1.6%
to $122.42 billion.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In the fourth quarter, the deficit was $28.75 billion, a
slight revision from the department's initial calculation of
$28.81 billion for the period.
   The quarterly balance-of-payments report differs from the
government's monthly merchandise trade numbers by excluding
military trade and making certain adjustments for timing,
insurance coverage and valuation. The monthly trade reports
are followed more closely than the quarterly numbers, but
generally both show the same trends.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900529-0119
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900529-0119.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Major Japanese Steel Concerns Report
   Record Pretax Profit for Fiscal 1989
   ----
   Special to The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/29/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   JAPAN J.NIP J.KOB J.SMM J.KWS J.NSS J.NKK
</CO>
<IN>
STEEL MANUFACTURERS (STL)
EARNINGS (ERN)
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
</IN>
<LP>
   TOKYO -- Most of Japan's six major steel companies Friday
reported record pretax earnings in fiscal 1989 ended on March
31, 1990, owing to strong domestic demand.
   Only NKK Corp., the second largest manufacturer, showed a
pretax earnings decline. NKK's pretax earnings declined 19%,
mostly as a result of a change in the way the company
measures depreciation costs.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The others -- Nippon Steel Corp., Kobe Steel Ltd.,
Sumitomo Metal Industries Ltd., Kawasaki Steel Corp., and
Nisshin Steel Co., reported healthy pretax profit growth,
though Sumitomo's net income declined, as did NKK's.
   Nippon Steel, Sumitomo Metal Industries and Kawasaki Steel
decided to increase their dividends for the year.
   Company officials said vigorous demand from such major
domestic steel users as construction companies, auto makers
and machinery manufacturers helped buoy sales and profit,
though recovering export prices also made contributions.
   "This was the best year we have ever had," an official at
Nippon Steel said. "Domestic demand was very strong because
of economic growth and that accounted for most of the gains."
   "Things were very good, overall," an official at Kobe
Steel agreed. "Exports to some countries like China were
sluggish, but domestic demand more than made up for the
drop."
   The brisk earnings gains in the latest reporting year for
most companies presented a stark contrast with their
performance only a few years back when, battered by the yen's
sharp upturn and by the growing inroads into the world market
by other Asian countries like South Korea and Taiwan, they
suffered serious setbacks. In an attempt to tide over the
trouble, the steel companies laid off workers and branched
into new areas of business.
   Nippon Steel's pretax earnings climbed 26% to 202.34
billion yen ($1.34 billion) from 160.361 billion yen. Net
income showed a 55% upsurge, going up to 97.054 billion yen,
or 14.09 yen a share, from 62.728 billion yen, or 9.45 yen a
share.
   Sales were 2.573 trillion yen, up 7.9% from 2.385 trillion
yen.
   Nippon Steel, encouraged by its performance, decided to
raise the dividend for the year to six yen from five yen in
the previous fiscal year.
   Nippon Steel's strong performance came despite an 83% jump
in extraordinary losses, a result of investment under its
medium-range program to improve production efficiency and
streamline operations.
   The company, however, posted extraordinary gains of 6.128
billion yen, though it had no such profit in fiscal 1988.
   Steel sales increased 4.8% to 2.242 trillion yen, while
the engineering division showed a 35% jump with sales at
259.400 billion yen.
   Exports dipped 3.7% to 600.001 billion yen. Officials at
Nippon Steel, as did those at other companies, said shipments
to China registered a conspicuous drop as that country pushed
an economic adjustment program.
   NKK's pretax earnings were 82.081 billion yen, in contrast
with 101.058 billion yen in the previous fiscal year. Net
income fell 27% to 30.847 billion yen, or 8.75 yen a share,
from 42.013 billion yen, or 13.17 yen a share.
   Sales showed a modest 1.3% gain, inching to 1.277 trillion
yen from 1.261 trillion yen.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900529-0118
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900529-0118.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Summer Electric Capacity Seen Meeting
   Demand, but Some Brownouts Predicted
   ----
   By Bill Paul
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/29/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B9C
</SO>
<CO>
   MHP
</CO>
<IN>
ELECTRIC UTILITIES (ELC)
</IN>
<LP>
   Residents of the nation's capital should hope that the
only hot air they get next month is the political kind.
   The North American Electric Reliability Council predicted
that, because of the temporary outage of a big power plant,
hotter-than-normal weather in June may necessitate voltage
reductions, also known as brownouts, in the
Washington-Baltimore area.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   While generally imperceptible, voltage reductions force
machines to work harder, making them more trouble-prone.
Moreover, a utility doesn't trim its output until after it
has publicly appealed to its customers to voluntarily turn
off air conditioners and other electrical appliances.
   Otherwise, said the utility industry's Princeton,
N.J.-based forecasting unit, there should generally be enough
electrical capacity to meet this summer's peak demands. It
added, however, that under certain circumstances -- very hot
weather and unexpected plant outages -- the Southeast and
Mid-Atlantic regions could have problems. It further said
that Midwest utilities may be forced to trim sales to other
regions if an unexpectedly high number of power plants go
down.
   Two private power-supply forecasters offered somewhat
different assessments. In Lexington, Mass., Larry Mackovich,
director of electricity services for McGraw-Hill Co.'s DRI
Energy unit, said the only area where problems might occur
this summer is the Mid-Atlantic region, specifically,
Pennsylvania, New Jersey and Maryland.
   Noting that utilities in that region are operating with
only about a 13% reserve margin -- 17% to 20% is preferred --
Mr. Mackovich said there is a 50% chance of voltage
reductions, and a 10% to 15% chance of rolling blackouts,
during the first half of August, but only if the weather is
hot and if there are unexpected plant outages.
   Rolling blackouts occur when one section after another of
a utility's service territory is blacked out by the utility,
generally for a few hours at a time. Utilities employ the
tactic only after brownouts have failed.
   In New York, Marie Corio, president of Applied Economic
Research Co., said the greater problem is in Virginia and
North and South Carolina. Ms. Corio explained that a number
of plants in that region aren't expected to be available this
summer. Thus, she said, if the weather's hot, there's a 50%
chance of brownouts and a 10% or so chance of rolling
blackouts in Virginia and the Carolinas in July and August.
   Ms. Corio agreed with Mr. Mackovich's assessment of
Pennsylvania, New Jersey and Maryland. She further agreed
with the Council that Midwest utilities might have to trim
their "off-system" sales; Mr. Mackovich doubted that would
happen. Both said they didn't know enough about the
Baltimore-Washington situation to comment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900529-0117
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900529-0117.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Machine Tool
   Orders in April
   Were Up 19%
   ---
   Small Manufacturers Aren't
   Feeling a Credit Crunch,
   Industry Executives Say
   ----
   By Ralph E. Winter
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/29/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A8
</SO>
<IN>
INDUSTRIAL EQUIPMENT, MACHINE TOOLS (IND)
ECONOMIC AND MONETARY INDICATORS (EMI)
ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)
</IN>
<LP>
   The nation's manufacturers are buying machinery somewhat
more willingly than they did three months ago, machine tool
producers say. And there's no indication so far that even
small manufacturers are feeling a credit crunch, industry
executives add.
   U.S. machine tool plants in April received $289.5 million
of orders, a 19% rise from $242.6 million a year earlier,
according to the NMTBA -- The Association for Manufacturing
Technology , a McLean, Va., trade group. Last month's orders
were up 8.9% from March, and were 49% higher than February's
$194.6 million, this year's low.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Unlike March, when a big Soviet order bolstered the total,
the April rise resulted from increased ordering by U.S.
factories.
   However, machine tool distributors, who handle
foreign-made machines as well as those produced in the U.S.,
reported a sharp drop in orders during April. An order index
published by the American Machine Tool Distributors'
Association, Rockville Pike, Md., dropped 27% from the
year-earlier month. The index is quite volatile, and the
March report was unusually strong, which suggests that the
April drop may result from an accidental bunching of orders
rather than the start of a downtrend.
   Machine tools are complex part-making machines ranging
from computer-controlled lathes and machining centers to
metal-forming presses. Orders are a good indicator of
spending by durable-goods manufacturers because machine tools
shape most metal parts.
   "Business is very good," said Stephen M. Peterson, vice
president, sales, for Giddings &amp; Lewis Inc., Fond du Lac,
Wis. "We see some real confidence out there among our
customers."
   Jet engine manufacturers, construction equipment concerns
and pump manufacturers have been ordering actively, Mr.
Peterson said. "We're getting some military business, though
not as much as last year, and there's quite a bit of activity
in the oil country" after a prolonged period when the oil
field equipment industry was dormant.
   Also, Giddings &amp; Lewis recently sold two
computer-controlled manufacturing cells in the Far East, one
in Singapore and the other in Taiwan, he said. Cells consist
of several machine tools served by automated
materials-handling equipment and controlled by a computer
that can make a variety of parts without a human operator.
   "Our second quarter is better than the first," said Donald
D. Bowers, president of Leblond Makino Machine Tool Co.,
Mason, Ohio. "Companies committed to long-term objectives" in
improving productivity and product quality "are ordering
equipment to carry out those programs," he added. But other
companies that base their equipment buying on the immediate
business outlook are holding back.
   Auto companies and auto suppliers remain a weak spot, said
Harold J. Winch, president of Minster Machine Co., a major
producer of stamping presses in Minster, Ohio. "They're
weighing a lot of decisions right now, including plastic
versus metal parts, government fuel economy standards, clean
air legislation and next year's auto sales outlook." Until
they hash out those decisions, auto concerns are deferring
some capital spending decisions.
   Machine tool producers frequently sell to small machine
shops, which would be among the marginal borrowers denied
loans in a credit crunch. So far, at least, that doesn't
appear to be happening, machine tool executives say.
   "I haven't seen any evidence of a credit crunch," said
Minster Machine's Mr. Winch. "A company with a decent balance
sheet doesn't have any more trouble getting a loan" than it
did last year.
   There has been concern that banks would tighten lending
standards following the high loan losses sustained by banks
and thrifts, and the resulting closer scrutiny of bank loan
portfolios by government regulators. There's been some
tightening on real estate development lending, but
manufacturing has been affected relatively little so far.
   "There is no evidence of a credit crisis . . . nor is
there much reason to expect one," said Gail D. Fosler, chief
economist for the Conference Board, a New York business and
economic research group. The slower growth in bank loans
results from lower loan demand in a slow-growing economy
rather than more stringent lending standards, she said.
   April orders for lathes, grinders, milling machines,
machining centers, boring mills and other machines that shape
metal parts by cutting rose 35% to $206.9 million from $152.8
million a year earlier. However, April 1989 was the first
month of an order slowdown by the auto industry, after 18
months of active buying, making for an easier comparison.
Nonetheless, the latest month's orders were up 8.9% from
March's $198.2 million, despite the inclusion in March of a
$38 million Soviet order received by Cross &amp; Trecker Corp.,
Bloomfield Hills, Mich.
   Orders last month for metal-forming presses and other
machines to shape metal with pressure were $82.6 million, the
NMTBA said, down 8% from the year-earlier month's $89.8
million, but up 22% from $67.7 million in March.
   Shipments of all types of machine tools by domestic plants
totaled $258.2 million, a 3.5% rise from $249.6 million in
April 1989.
   ---
