<HL>
   Argentina Revives $1.4 Billion Accord
   With IMF and Sets Talks With Banks
   ----
   By Peter Truell
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/29/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A8
</SO>
<CO>
   LATAM
</CO>
<IN>
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
BANKS (BNK)
INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND STATISTICS (IEN)
</IN>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- Argentina, striving to repair relations with
its foreign creditors, has revived a $1.4 billion loan
agreement with the International Monetary Fund and will begin
negotiations Thursday on resuming payments to its main
commercial bank creditors.
   Late Friday, the IMF's executive board cleared a $240
million loan to Argentina, after the board had approved
revised targets for an economic program originally agreed to
in November 1989. Argentina can draw the $240 million
immediately; it previously had drawn another $240 million of
the $1.4 billion credit. The IMF had held up further
disbursements until Argentina had set revised targets for
such important economic indicators as inflation and the size
of the government deficit.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The Latin American country has succeeded in reviving its
agreement with the IMF after two months of much-improved
management under Economy Minister Erman Gonzalez. Inflation
has moderated, and the government even seems to be balancing
its budget.
   The renewed IMF agreement will, for the first time, allow
Argentina to set aside 25% of what remains of the $1.4
billion credit to allow it to pursue plans to reduce its bank
debt. Faced with a total of about $60 billion of foreign debt
-- with more than half of that owed to commercial banks,
Argentine officials are eager to try such strategies.
   Argentina's leading commercial bank creditors struggled
hard -- but failed -- to ensure that the country made an
interest payment to them before it could restore its
relations with the IMF. They also had hoped to extract an
interest payment from the Argentines as the price of resuming
talks on Argentina's approximately $30.5 billion of medium-
and long-term foreign bank debt. But that strategy also
didn't succeed.
   Nevertheless, the banks remain hopeful that they will
receive a payment around the time the talks start in New
York. "I think that they'll make a payment when we start
talking," said a senior U.S. banker. Argentina is as much as
$6 billion in arrears on interest payments to banks, having
not paid interest to them for as much as two years. It is
struggling to restructure its economy, and is reluctant to
make payments to banks from its estimated $1 billion of
foreign-exchange reserves.
   In a statement released in New York, William Rhodes, the
Citicorp executive who heads the 13-bank committee that
negotiates with Argentina, and Javier Gonzalez Fraga, the
vice president of the Argentine central bank, said they had
agreed to resume negotiations. Mr. Rhodes said they will
discuss "the resumption of a regular flow of payments by
Argentina to commercial bank creditors" on the country's
medium-term and long-term public-sector debt.
   Argentina's progress with its foreign creditors contrasts
with Brazil, which has yet to reach agreement with the IMF
and reopen talks with foreign bank creditors. Brazil, which
now has interest payment arrears to its commercial banks that
amount to about $5 billion, seems to be preoccupied with
trying to improve the enactment of its economic plan.
   Its economy minister, Zelia Cardoso de Mello, visited
senior bankers in New York recently. They seemed
disappointed. "She's not doing much in the way of listening,"
said one. With reserves of as much as $8 billion, the bankers
reckon that Brazil could start to clean up its payments
arrears before they become unmanageably large.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900529-0090
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900529-0090.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Technology:
   Adobe, Apple Send
   Mixed Signals;
   Stocks End Lower
   ----
   By Richard B. Schmitt
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/29/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4
</SO>
<CO>
   AAPL ADBE
</CO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)
SOFTWARE (SOF)
COMPUTERS AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (CPR)
</IN>
<LP>
   Apple Computer Inc. may well be Adobe Systems Inc.'s
largest customer, but last week the two companies had a hard
time computing together.
   On Friday, Adobe's stock plunged $15.25, or about 30%,
despite the company's raising of a disappointing earnings
projection made late Thurday. The revision followed an
unusual public debate between Apple and Adobe over the
strength of sales of Apple laser printers that use Adobe
software.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   On Thursday, Adobe surprised analysts by saying earnings
and revenue for the second quarter ending June 1 would be
sharply below analysts' expectations. And one of the main
reasons it cited was a 23% drop in revenue from Apple
compared with the first quarter.
   But Apple said the falloff wasn't that sharp, and Friday,
before markets opened, the two companies issued separate news
releases to that effect.
   Adobe said it had obtained revenue estimates from Apple
for the months of April and May and then used that
information for its quarterly estimate. Then, "Apple got back
to us and said the April number provided had been incorrect,"
Adobe said.
   An Apple spokeswoman tells a different story. "Adobe did
receive preliminary numbers for the months of March and
April. Adobe called to confirm the {quarterly} trend, but we
told them we did not agree with their analysis. They decided
to issue a press release anyway."
   In national over-the-counter trading Friday, Adobe stock
closed at $35.25 a share on volume of 8.5 million shares. The
drop, which was credited with prompting a wave of selling of
technology issues, came a day after Adobe's stock climbed
$1.50 to a high of $50.50 on anticipation that the company
would release positive news. Apple shares closed at $40, down
$2.
   In its revised forecast Friday, Adobe said it expects
earnings of 29 cents to 37 cents a share, on revenue of $33
million to $36 million. Although higher than the forecast
issued the day before, it was well below some analysts'
estimates of 51 cents a share and revenue of about $42
million. In the year-earlier quarter, Adobe earned $7.6
million, or 35 cents a share, on revenue of $28.1 million.
   Some analysts are still concerned that Apple's printer
sales are lagging, in part because of increased competition
from Hewlett-Packard Co. The Apple spokeswoman said the
company's printer sales are still "healthy."
   Certainly Apple's relations with Adobe aren't as close as
they once were. In July, Apple decided to divest its 16.4%
stake in Adobe, and last fall, Apple and Microsoft Corp. said
they would develop printer software that would compete
against Adobe's.
   Meanwhile, Adobe is only beginning to get some lift from
other potentially lucrative revenue sources, including
International Business Machines Corp., which in March said it
would start offering Adobe software with its OS/2
personal-computer operating system.
   Separately, Invest/Net, a North Miami, Fla., firm that
tracks insider buying and selling, said that from Jan. 1
through April 30, Adobe insiders sold 501,153 shares,
compared with a total of 293,032 shares in all of 1989. In
April, a total of 90,000 shares was sold by Adobe Chief
Executive Officer John Warnock at between $37.75 and $38.25,
and a total of 40,000 was sold by Adobe President Charles
Geschke at between $39 and $40 each. Adobe officials couldn't
be reached to comment on the selling.
   ---
   Georgette Jasen contributed to this article.
</TEXT>
