<HL>
   Pension Insurer
   Is Dealt a Blow
   In LTV Decision
   ----
   By Karen Blumenthal
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/29/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B7
</SO>
<CO>
   LTV LABOR
</CO>
<IN>
BANKRUPTCIES (BCY)
STEEL MANUFACTURERS (STL)
AEROSPACE (ARO)
CDS, INTEREST RATES, COMMERCIAL PAPER (FIN)
</IN>
<GV>
FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)
</GV>
<LP>
   The judge overseeing LTV Corp.'s bankruptcy-law
proceedings dealt the Pension Benefit Guaranty Corp. another
blow last week, concluding that the pension insurer isn't
entitled to special treatment in the case and that its $2.23
billion claim against LTV's estate is way too high.
   While the decision was hailed as a positive one for LTV's
other creditors, the federal pension insurance and regulatory
agency warned that the ruling could reduce its potential
recoveries from LTV by as much as $1 billion. Such a
reduction would exacerbate the financial troubles at the
agency, which currently has about $3.2 billion in assets and
$4.2 billion in liabilities, the PBGC said.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The ruling by federal bankruptcy Judge Burton R. Lifland
must be affirmed by a federal district judge to be adopted.
The PBGC said it plans to challenge the decision in federal
court.
   Disputes between the Dallas-based steel, aerospace and
defense concern and the Washington-based PBGC have become the
centerpiece of LTV's almost four-year-long tangle with
bankruptcy-law proceedings. The company sought protection
from creditors under Chapter 11 of the federal Bankruptcy
Code in 1986, in part because it couldn't continue to fund
its steel unit's pension plans. The PBGC terminated three of
those plans in 1987, assuming those plans' liabilities to
keep its losses from growing.
   But the agency ordered LTV to reinstate those plans and
pick up the tab after LTV implemented new retirement
benefits. LTV sued, and both a district court and a federal
appeals court ruled that the agency couldn't force LTV to
resume the old plans without proving that the company could
afford them. The U.S. Supreme Court heard arguments in the
case in February, but hasn't issued a decision.
   Judge Lifland's ruling last week affects four pension
plans, including one that isn't involved in the Supreme Court
case. If his decision is affirmed, last week's ruling would
require that the PBGC be treated as a general unsecured
creditor in LTV's reorganization, rather than as a taxing
entity as the PBGC had argued it was. Under bankruptcy laws,
taxing agencies like the Internal Revenue Service are given a
higher priority in the reorganization and are paid ahead of
other creditors.
   In addition, Judge Lifland argued that bankruptcy laws,
not pension laws, should govern the discount rate that the
agency uses to calculate how much it needs to recover from
LTV to pay out future pension benefits. The PBGC, citing
pension laws, used a 7.5% discount rate in calculating its
$2.23 billion in claims. But most pension and investment
funds reap returns much greater than 7.5% on their
investments. Using a discount rate of, say, 10.5% would
reduce the agency's claim by $500 million or more.
   In assessing the agency's claims, Judge Lifland also found
some to be redundant. The PBGC said that based on the judge's
ruling, it could expect to recover perhaps $230 million from
the LTV's reorganization, instead of the $500 million to $1.5
billion it had hoped for.
   However, the ruling is "absolutely very good" for LTV
creditors who have to divide up just over $4 billion to
satisfy claims that now exceed $7 billion, said Gary Hindes,
chairman of the Delaware Bay Co., a brokerage concern
specializing in distressed companies. However, a
reorganization plan isn't expected until the pension disputes
are resolved.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900529-0082
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900529-0082.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Labor Letter:
   A Special News Report on People
   And Their Jobs in Offices,
   Fields and Factories
   ----
   Compiled by Selwyn Feinstein
</HL>
<DATE>
05/29/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<CO>
   LABOR JAPAN
</CO>
<IN>
INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND STATISTICS (IEN)
INSURANCE (INS)
</IN>
<LP>
   WEAK HIRING seems likely in second half. But bright spots
persist.
   International Business Machines Corp. plans to cut 10,000
U.S. jobs this year. Still, it looks for programmers,
engineers and holders of advanced degrees. Union Pacific
Corp. wants to bargain reductions in unionized rail crews.
But it anticipates adding 400 to 600 truck drivers, 100
professionals for a new telemarketing center and 30 oil and
gas workers. Owens-Corning Fiberglas Corp. calls its hiring
plan "conservative." Yet it can't recruit enough engineers.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Homes Corp. says "all we're doing is replacing people
lost to attrition." Eastern Co. expects little change.
Stevens Graphics, though, wants to add 25 to 50 new workers
in the second half to increase marketing efforts in Western
Europe and the Eastern bloc. And Pier 1 Imports says its
employment has jumped to 9,000 workers from 7,800 a year ago,
and it expects to add 15 employees for each new store it
opens every 4 1/2 days.
   Apple Bank is "in a replacement mode" but it has trouble
finding qualified workers for entry-level jobs.
                                                                                                       

   LABOR SHORTAGE grows more worrisome in Japan. Can you wait
five years?
   Last year, for the first time in 14 years, the number of
job openings exceeded the number of job seekers in Japan, and
the imbalance is getting worse in 1990, says the Fuji
Economic Review. But Japan's bustling export trade isn't
responsible. The review lays the current worker shortage to a
strong increase in domestic demand in Japan.
   It may take five years, but the shortage will ease, the
publication says. One reason for its optimism: "The Japanese
economy has grown about 5% annually for nearly three years.
This pace will not likely be maintained." And Japan, it says,
could recruit more males over 55 and females between the ages
of 25 and 44. Far fewer women of child-bearing age work in
Japan than in the U.S., it observes.
                                                                                                       

   IN MIDDLE AGE, some still fantasize about what we'll do
when we grow up.
   Most people between 35 and 54 continue to daydream about
their careers: to anticipate a job change, compensate for
something missing, or escape from day-to-day tedium. But
Judith Meyerowitz, in a doctoral dissertation at Columbia's
Teachers College, says something seems to happen at age 45.
We shift from daydreaming about our current jobs to
fantasizing about what we will do in the future.
   The study -- based on interviews with 60 bankers, teachers
and university personnel -- finds we look for different
rewards as we grow older. In early career lives, men
particularly dream of control, pay and recognition. By 45,
these daydreams turn to personal expression, even aesthetics.
"Women, too, look inward as they grow older," Ms. Meyerowitz
says. "But as men enter late middle age they seem to
fantasize more about a less complex life while women talk
more about owning their own businesses as a way to assert
themselves."
   Most fantasies are realistic. Still, one librarian dreams
of playing shortstop for the St. Louis Cardinals.
                                                                                                       

   RATING THE BOSS: Only 36% of the workers surveyed by
consultant Hay Group from 1987 through 1989 thought their
companies were run well. But that's an improvement from the
30% who expressed such confidence in 1981-82.
                                                                                                       

   STRESS RIDES one way. Three of four managers say stress at
work sometimes affects their home life, finds a study by
Dunhill Personnel System and Columbia Business School. But
only one in three managers brings stress from home to work.
                                                                                                       

   REIMBURSEMENT ACCOUNTS grow. Consultant Foster Higgins
says 41% of all companies, up from 30% a year ago, let
workers set aside pretax dollars to pay for health and
dependent care. A further 22% are considering the benefit.
                                                                                                       

   TRAINING WORKERS at colleges costs companies $2.9 billion
a year, the American Society for Training and Development
says. Total training expenditures come to $30 billion, of
which $9 billion goes to outside contractors, including the
schools.
                                                                                                       

   WORKERS APLENTY are ready to mow lawns. But sprayers often
need a license.
   In Southern California, immigrants from Mexico and Central
and South America assure an ample supply of hands for routine
lawn chores. But Green Scene in Tarzana, Calif., has a hard
time finding workers fluent enough in English to deal with
customers. To apply pesticides and herbicides, it needs
people with a high school education "who can read and
understand labels."
   Atlanta firms, too, see no shortage of applicants for
$6-an-hour lawn-cutting jobs. But Alfred L. Simpson &amp; Co.
says even $8 to $10 an hour isn't enough incentive for some
workers to handle chemicals. "A lot of people are afraid of
pesticides," it says. And Landscapes Inc. worries that lawn
labor is going to become a lot scarcer. "We're having to do a
much smarter job of hiring" to secure people who "are
prepared for their jobs and will stick with them."
   Carey's Professional Turf in Des Moines says spring hires
often weary of the work by summer's heat.
                                                                                                       

   THE CHECKOFF: One in two senior executives never takes
unsolicited calls and most see only 10% of their mail, says
Blue Chip Marketing Group. . . . "Additional time spent on
breaks at work apparently does raise earnings (i.e.,
productivity), but not to the same extent as does additional
time spent working," concludes a study by the National Bureau
of Economic Research.
</TEXT>
