<HL>
   International Brief -- Mondadori S.p.A.:
   Leading Italian Publisher's
   Net for 1989 Plunged 48%
</HL>
<DATE>
05/29/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A10
</SO>
<CO>
   I.MND
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
</IN>
<LP>
   Mondadori S.p.A., Italy's largest publishing concern, said
1989 net income plunged 48% to 54 billion lire ($4.4 million)
from 103.5 billion lire a year earlier.
   Directors proposed reducing dividends to 180 lire an
ordinary share from 380 lire, and to 200 lire each for
preferred and savings shares from 400 lire.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Mondadori blamed the earnings drop on costs stemming from
last year's acquisition of L'Editoriale Espresso S.p.A., a
Rome-based publisher. Revenue jumped to 2.367 trillion lire
in 1989 from 1.495 trillion lire in 1988. Excluding special
items, profit fell 31% to 138.3 billion lire. Debt totaled
372.5 billion lire at the end of 1989, compared with net
liquidity of 220 billion lire a year earlier. The parent's
profit fell to 73.9 billion lire from 78.4 lire and sales
rose to 1.106 trillion lire from 1.091 trillion lire.
   Mondadori is at the center of a conflict between the media
magnate Silvio Berlusconi, who was named chairman in January,
and the financier Carlo De Benedetti, who lost control of
Mondadori in December; the two sides are in talks on a
compromise that may break up the company.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900529-0075
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900529-0075.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   International Brief -- Mitsubishi Motors Corp.:
   Unconsolidated Pretax Profit
   For Fiscal Year Rose 23%
</HL>
<DATE>
05/29/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   J.MOT
</CO>
<IN>
AUTOMOBILES (AUT)
EARNINGS (ERN)
</IN>
<LP>
   Mitsubishi Motors Corp., Japan's third-largest auto maker,
reported that its unconsolidated pretax profit for the year
ended March 31 increased 23% to 41.42 billion yen ($274.4
million) from 33.72 billion yen a year earlier.
   Operating profit rose 11% to 48.77 billion yen from 44.07
billion yen, contributing to a 58% rise in net income to
20.24 billion yen from 12.84 billion yen. Per-share earnings
rose to 23.71 yen from 16.59 yen.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Sales climbed 6.7% to 2.026 trillion yen from 1.899
trillion yen, boosted by an increase in domestic sales and a
surge in exported parts for overseas production; revenue from
the latter more than doubled to 161.6 billion yen from 69.8
billion yen. Interest and dividends income rose 28% to 20.55
billion yen.
   The company decided to extend a dividend of 5.5 yen a
common share, up 10% from five yen a year earlier.
   Mitsubishi predicted sales of 2.2 trillion yen in fiscal
1991, up 8.6%; net income is seen at 22 billion yen, up 8.7%,
and pretax profit at 46 billion yen, up 11%.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900529-0074
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900529-0074.
</DOCID>
