<HL>
   Boeing Gets Order
   From Iberia Airlines
   Valued at $1 Billion
</HL>
<DATE>
05/29/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C9
</SO>
<CO>
   BA E.ILA
</CO>
<IN>
AIRLINES (AIR)
AEROSPACE (ARO)
</IN>
<LP>
   SEATTLE -- Boeing Co. confirmed that it received firm
orders valued at $1 billion for 16 757 jetliners from Spain's
Iberia Airlines.
   The order also includes options Iberia secured on 12 more
of the jetliners plus spare parts and training. Engine
selection will be made at a later date, Boeing said.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The order, disclosed by Iberia in Madrid last Friday,
calls for the airplanes to be outfitted for 188 passengers,
86 in business class and 102 in tourist. Iberia said the
jetliners will be delivered starting in 1993 through the
third quarter of 1994.
   Iberia, which is controlled by Spain's National Industrial
Institute, has said it is in the midst of renovating much of
its fleet, which consists of 84 aircraft ranging from
McDonnell Douglas DC-9s to widebody Boeing 747s.
   The airline's new Boeing airplanes will replace some of
its 35 Boeing 727 aircraft, Iberia said. They will be used
primarily on its route network to European, African and
Middle Eastern destinations.
   Last year, Iberia ordered eight airbus A-340 airplanes and
took options on four others, as well as 17 McDonnell Douglas
MD-87 aircraft, at a combined cost of $1.1 billion. Iberia
has said it expects to replace its entire fleet by 2000.
   Seattle-based Boeing said that Iberia's order for 16 of
its 757s brings to 648 the number of 757s ordered by 33
customers including Iberia. The aerospace concern said that
so far this year, it has had orders for 154 of the aircraft
valued at about $12.4 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900529-0063
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900529-0063.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Statewide Bancorp.
   Boosts Loan Reserves,
   Omits Cash Dividend
</HL>
<DATE>
05/29/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B9B
</SO>
<CO>
   STWB
</CO>
<IN>
DIVIDENDS (DIV)
</IN>
<GV>
TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)
</GV>
<LP>
   TOMS RIVER, N.J. -- Statewide Bancorp. said it increased
its allowance for loan losses by $30 million, omitted its
cash dividend and agreed to a close review of its main
subsidiary bank.
   The loan-loss provision rose to $50 million from $20
million at March 31, as some real estate loans continued to
deteriorate and the New Jersey real estate market remained
uncertain, the bank said. One of its loan participations had
been criticized by the Comptroller of the Currency, the
principal regulator of both of Statewide's subsidiaries.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Statewide, which has about $2 billion in assets, said it
believes the new provision is adequate, but it didn't rule
out further increases. "We can't hold out to people that it
definitely won't get worse," said Charles Sanders, the bank's
secretary.
   Statewide said the suspension of its quarterly cash
dividend, which was 20 cents a share, will take effect in the
second quarter and continue indefinitely. Douglas Johnson,
president and chief executive officer, said the bank's
previous dividend payments have amounted to about $8 million
a year.
   Mr. Johnson said the suspension is intended to preserve
Statewide's "strong capital position," which he said is well
above regulatory requirements.
   The review of Statewide's lead subsidiary, First National
Bank of Toms River, is the result of an agreement with the
Comptroller of the Currency. It covers the adequacy of
loan-loss provisions and requires the development of plans to
strengthen assets, ensure adequate capitalization, and
improve supervision of bad loans.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
