<HL>
   Denison Mines Faces
   Selling More Assets
   To Meet Obligations
</HL>
<DATE>
05/29/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B9B
</SO>
<CO>
   DEN.A
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
DIVIDENDS (DIV)
</IN>
<LP>
   TORONTO -- Denison Mines Ltd., which is already trying to
sell its oil and gas assets, said it may have to put other
noncore assets on the block to meet its financial
obligations.
   Helen Roman-Barber, chairman and chief executive officer,
told the annual meeting that the company's plan to sell its
overseas oil and gas assets has "proved to be a difficult"
task.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Denison sold its Canadian oil and gas properties last
November for 44.6 million Canadian dollars (US$37.7 million).
Ms. Roman-Barber declined to place a value on the remaining
assets, which are in Spain, Egypt, Italy and Greece.
   "We are dealing with the prospect that the oil and gas
divestiture program may not provide us with sufficient funds
to meet our financial obligations," she said.
   The company has about C$316 million in debt and faces
payments of C$31 million this year and C$86 million in 1991.
It also will need about C$175 million next March to retract
its Series B preferred shares. The company has the option to
pay stock for the shares, but Ms. Roman-Barber said Denison
hopes to be able to pay cash.
   The company decided in 1989 to concentrate on its uranium
operations. But uranium prices are at all-time lows, and
Denison had a first-quarter loss of C$4.8 million, or 15
Canadian cents a share.
   On the Toronto Stock Exchange Friday, the company's Class
B shares fell one Canadian cent at C$1.13, well off the
issue's 52-week high of C$5.375.
   The company continues to have interests in potash and coal
mining, though it wrote off its entire interest in its only
remaining coal operation in 1986.
   Jake Fowler, president and chief operating officer,
wouldn't say which assets might be sold. "We like the potash
business very much, but our core business is uranium," he
said.
   Mr. Fowler also said the company won't pay dividends on
its common shares until "we're generating sufficient cash."
Denison doesn't have a set dividend policy. Previous payment
was a stock dividend in Class B shares equal to 24 Canadian
cents in Febuary 1989.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900529-0056
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900529-0056.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Merck's Losec Drug
   For Ulcers Obtains
   FDA Panel's Backing
</HL>
<DATE>
05/29/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   MRK
</CO>
<IN>
DRUG MANUFACTURERS (DRG)
</IN>
<GV>
FOOD AND DRUG ADMINISTRATION (FDA)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- An advisory committee of the Food and Drug
Administration recommended that the agency approve a Merck &amp;
Co. drug to treat acute duodenal ulcers.
   The drug, Losec, is currently marketed to treat other
disorders, including severe heartburn. The advisory committee
recommended extending its use to people suffering duodenal
ulcers that fail to respond to such other drugs as Tagamet,
manufactured by Smith Kline &amp; French Laboratories,
Philadelphia; and Zantac, made by Glaxo Inc., Research
Triangle Park., N.C.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The advisory committee urged that Losec be approved only
for short-term use. Merck spokesman Gary Bruell said that the
company requested approval only for short-term use because
the drug was a powerful inhibitor of acid secretion. He added
that ulcer treatment is "typically short term."
   The advisory committee previously had expressed concern
about a possible cancer risk associated with Losec, according
to Dr. Stephen Fredd, director of the FDA's division of
gastro-intestinal and coagulation drug products. But Dr.
Fredd said that the committee was reassured by new human data
supplied by the company, and now agreed with the company that
the drug is safe for short-term use.
   A written statement released by Merck noted that two
studies of rats receiving Losec over their two-year lifespan
showed a dose-related increase in gastric carcinoid tumors.
The company, which is based in Rahway, N.J., said it found no
evidence of cancer risk for human patients, but that more
human data was needed "to rule out the possibility of an
increased risk of tumors from long-term therapy with Losec."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900529-0055
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900529-0055.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Avery, Dennison
   Plan to Merge
   In Stock Swap
   ---
   Deal, Valued at $456 Million,
   To Form a Leading Firm
   In Office-Products Field
   ----
   By Rhonda L. Rundle and Joseph Pereira
   Staff Reporters of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/29/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A6
</SO>
<CO>
   AVY DSN WNEWS
</CO>
<IN>
OFFICE EQUIPMENT (OFF)
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   Avery International Corp. and Dennison Manufacturing Co.
agreed to merge in a stock swap with an indicated value of
$456 million that would create one of the nation's largest
office-products concerns with $2.5 billion in annual sales.
   The successor company, Avery Dennison Corp., would be
dominated by the board of Avery International and based at
its corporate offices in Pasadena, Calif. Besides marker
pens, stationery and other office supplies, Avery Dennison
would sell self-adhesive materials, product fasteners, and
printing and labeling systems.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Under the agreement, approved by the boards of both
companies last week, Dennison shareholders would receive 1.12
shares of Avery common stock for each share held of Dennison
common.
   In New York Stock Exchange composite trading Friday,
Dennison shares jumped $8.375 to $27.375 on turnover of 1.7
million shares. Avery shares fell $2.25 to $26.25; 1.8
million shares changed hands. Dennison has 15.5 million
shares outstanding; Avery has 44.2 million shares
outstanding.
   Avery and Dennison described the transaction as a
"strategic merger" of companies with "complementary"
products. Dennison, based in Framingham, Mass., is stronger
in certain East Coast markets, while Avery is stronger in the
Midwest and on the West Coast. About 35% of Avery Dennison's
sales would be in overseas markets that are growing more
quickly than domestic ones.
   Charles D. Miller, Avery chairman and chief executive
officer, would retain those titles at Avery Dennison. The
merger would create a strong global competitor on the eve of
the integration of the European Community in 1992, he said.
Avery Dennison also would be a "more important supplier" to a
growing group of office-supply superstores.
   The emergence of superstores such as Staples Inc., which
sells stationery goods at big discounts, has put strong
downward pressure on wholesale office-supply prices. Because
of this trend, there will be more consolidations like the
Avery-Dennison deal, analysts said. Some of the two
companies' biggest competitors are Minnesota Mining &amp;
Manufacturing Co. in St. Paul, Minn.; Esselte AB of
Stockholm, Sweden, and American Brands Inc., Greenwich, Conn.
   The chairmen of Dennison and Avery have known each other
for 15 years. Mr. Miller said he proposed a merger with
Dennison in 1987 that fell apart at the last minute over
price and "organization structure." The latest talks were
initiated by Dennison in March, Mr. Miller said.
   Nelson S. Gifford, Dennison chairman and chief executive
officer, would become vice chairman of Avery Dennison. The
board would include Avery's 12 current directors and four
Dennison directors. The combined companies would have 19,000
employees, of which more than one-quarter would be overseas.
   Analysts generally agreed that the companies are a good
fit, but some of them worried that Dennison's problems might
rub off on Avery. "Conceptually {the merger} makes sense;
making it work is a completely different ballgame," said
David Nelson, an analyst at Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. Avery
could have trouble integrating Dennison, which is
restructuring, he said.
   Last December, citing "a rapid slowdown" in its domestic
orders, Dennison announced a plan to cut costs by $10 million
annually. By the end of the first quarter, Dennison had let
go 400 employees, or 4% of its work force. As conditions
continued to deteriorate, the company said it would
re-evaluate its assets for possible downsizing.
   For the year ended Dec. 31, 1989, Dennison's profit
plunged 24% to $29.1 million, or $1.82 a share, from $37.2
million, or $2.35 a share, the prior year. Its 1989 sales
edged up to $770.9 million from $721.8 million the year
before. Reflecting its lackluster earnings, Dennison's stock
price has declined from a 52-week high of $32.875.
   Avery sales rose 10% to $1.73 billion from $1.58 billion
for the year ended Nov. 30, 1989. Net income increased 11% to
$86.5 million, or $1.96 a share, from $77.7 million, or $1.77
a share.
   If the merger is completed, Avery management said it would
recommend a quarterly cash dividend of 18 cents a share.
Avery currently pays a quarterly per-share dividend of 16
cents, or 64 cents a year. Dennison pays an annual dividend
of $1.32 a share.
   The merger is subject to shareholder and regulatory
approvals, but analysts doubted that antitrust or other
obstacles would emerge. Certain Avery affiliates and employee
benefit plans expected to approve the merger hold about 25%
of Avery shares. Dennison directors and officers and an
employee stock ownership trust expected to vote for the deal
own about 20% of Dennison's stock. Mr. Miller said he hoped
the merger could be completed by the end of September.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
