<HL>
   Business Brief -- Petro-Canada Inc.:
   Alberta Oil Refinery Is Shut
   In Wake of an Explosion
</HL>
<DATE>
05/29/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4
</SO>
<CO>
   CANDA
</CO>
<IN>
PETROLEUM (PET)
OIL, INTEGRATED MAJORS (OIL)
</IN>
<LP>
   Petro-Canada Inc. said its 120,000-barrel-a-day oil
refinery near Edmonton, Alberta, will be closed indefinitely
after an explosion late Thursday killed one worker and
injured two others.
   A Petro-Canada spokeswoman said in Calgary that the cause
of the blast wasn't immediately known and that an
investigation is under way.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The Edmonton plant accounts for about one-third of
Petro-Canada's refined crude output. The state-owned company,
which the Canadian government is preparing to take public, is
Canada's second-largest oil refiner, after Toronto-based
Imperial Oil Ltd., 70%-owned by Exxon Corp.
   The Edmonton refinery had been closed for about five weeks
for routine maintenance prior to the explosion, and was
scheduled to resume production shortly.
</TEXT>
