<HL>
   LEISURE &amp; ARTS:
   Time Off: Diversions and Excursions May 29-June 11
</HL>
<DATE>
05/29/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A12
</SO>
<LP>
   ART
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   Fleischer Museum, Scottsdale, Arizona: The first museum
dedicated to the California school of American impressionism
-- which capitalized on the intense sunlight and stunning
natural landscapes of the American West -- just opened its
doors to the public. Located inside the corporate
headquarters of Franchise Financial Corp. of America, the
15,000-square-foot museum showcases some 200 works by
painters such as Franz A. Bischoff (1864-1929), Guy Rose
(1867-1925) and William Wendt (1865-1946). The Perimeter
Center, 17207 North Perimeter Drive.
                                                                                                       

   Wichita Art Museum, Kansas: "We Like Ike" -- This unusual
show of more than 600 objects examines the Eisenhower
presidency and 1950s America. Visitors enter the show through
a hand-painted 12-foot-by-28-foot mural of the White House
and can see everything from Eisenhower portraits and campaign
materials (including the button shown here) to 30 of Mamie
Eisenhower's outfits; and 16 paintings by the president
himself, an accomplished amateur artist (see accompanying
illustration -- WSJ May 28, 1990). One gallery highlights the
Eisenhower years: the interstate highway system, the coming
of the jet age, and the addition of Alaska and Hawaii as
states. 169 Stackman, through July 8.
                                                                                                       

   Washington State Convention &amp; Trade Center, Seattle:
"Moscow: Treasures and Traditions" -- From Moscow and Kremlin
museums, more than 200 objects and works of art from the 15th
through 20th centuries. Icons, paintings, engravings, fine
metalwork in gold and silver, porcelains and historic
costumes reflect the creative life of the Soviet Union's
capital city. 8th Avenue and Pike Street, June 1-Sept. 30.
The show then moves to the International Gallery at the
Smithsonian Institution, Washington, D.C., October 1990
through February 1991.
                                                                                                       

   FILM
                                                                                                       

   American Museum of the Moving Image features dozens of
Hollywood's funniest short films in "Laughing Out Loud: The
Comedy Short 1925-1935," running from June 9-July 6. Look for
old favorites Laurel and Hardy, Ben Turpin, Zasu Pitts, Burns
and Allen, Buster Keaton and W.C. Fields. On June 16 the
museum will honor Stan Laurel's 100th birthday with a
presentation of five silent shorts starring Laurel without
Hardy. 35th Avenue at 36th Street, Astoria, Queens, New York.
For general information: (718) 784-0077; for travel
directions: (718) 784-4777.
                                                                                                       

   DANCE
                                                                                                       

   "Fresh Tracks": Maybe the next Petipa will emerge at this
biannual showcase for fledgling choreographers. The diverse
program offers works from six new talents selected by
audition. May 30-June 2, Dance Theater Workshop, 219 West
19th St., New York. (212) 924-0077.
                                                                                                       

   MUSIC
                                                                                                       

   Rockport Chamber Music Festival kicks off its ninth season
May 31 with a performance by the Manhattan and the Muir
string quartets of Brahms's Sextet in G Major and Dvorak's
Piano Trio in F Minor. Other featured artists at this
monthlong seaside event are the Amadeus Trio and the
Scarborough Chamber Players, June 7-10; the New Jersey
Chamber Music Society and the trumpet and organ duo
Giangiulio &amp; Riedo, June 14-17; and Directors &amp; Friends, a
gathering of musicians from previous seasons, June 21-24.
"Happy Birthday Rockport]" is a June 10 celebration of the
founding of Rockport with an emphasis on New England
composers. Rockport Art Association, Main Street. (508)
546-7391.
                                                                                                       

   San Francisco Opera offers a revival of its Nikolaus
Lehnhoff production of Wagner's "Ring." Cycles I and II will
be conducted by Viennese maestro Peter Schneider, whose
Bayreuth Festival credits include the 1984, '85 and '86
"Rings." British conductor Donald Runnicles, music director
of the Freiburg Opera, will preside over Cycles III and IV.
The cast includes Helga Dernesch, Hildegard Behrens, William
Johns, Gwyneth Jones and Gary Lakes. War Memorial Opera
House, 301 Van Ness Ave. June 6-July 1. (415) 864-3330.
                                                                                                       

   Hunters &amp; Collectors: Australia's band of the year
introduces the U.S. to the melodic, multitextured pop on its
new album "Ghost Nation" (Atlantic). It'll be opening for
countrymen Midnight Oil, no slouches either in the
guitar-powered pop department -- New York (Radio City), May
29-30; Wantagh, N.Y. (Jones Beach), June 1; Pittsburgh
(Palumbo Center), June 2; Cleveland (Blossom Music Theater),
June 3; Atlanta (Lakewood Amphitheater), June 5; St. Louis
(Fox Theater), June 7; Chicago (Poplar Creek), June 8;
Detroit (Pine Knob), June 9; Houston (Amphitheater), June 12;
Dallas (Starplex), June 13; Denver (Red Rocks), June 15; Salt
Lake City (Park West), June 16; Los Angeles (Universal
Amphitheater), June 19-20; San Diego (Open Air Amphitheater),
June 21; Irvine, Calif. (Irvine Meadows), June 22; Berkeley,
Calif. (Greek Theater), June 23; Seattle (Coliseum), June 25;
Vancouver (Thunderbird Stadium), June 26.
