<HL>
   International -- Foreign Insight:
   Iraqi President's Hoped-For Strong Show
   For U.S.-Soviet Summit Fails to Develop
   ----
   By Geraldine Brooks
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/29/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A10
</SO>
<CO>
   MDEST FREST
</CO>
<LP>
   When Iraqi President Saddam Hussein called for an Arab
summit in Baghdad, the plan was that Arab heads of state
would formulate a message to George Bush and Mikhail
Gorbachev when they meet this week in Washington.
   So far, the message seems unlikely to be the one Mr.
Hussein intended. He had hoped to demonstrate that the Arab
world is a united force, but yesterday's poorly attended
opening session indicated lingering disunity among Arab
nations. Calls in the government-controlled Iraqi press for
an Arab investment embargo and use of the "oil weapon"
against Western nations suggested that radical Arabs are
groping for ways to impose their will.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The main item on the agenda is the mass immigration of
Soviet Jews to Israel, which many Arab leaders, including
such moderates as Egypt's Hosni Mubarak and Jordan's King
Hussein, see as a threat to the peace process because the
influx may increase Israel's appetite for land. Yet the
summit opened without Hafez Assad of Syria, a crucial figure
in any attempt to pressure neighboring Israel. Mr. Assad
didn't attend because he and the Iraqi president have been
engaged in a feud for years. Lebanon, Syria's ally, also
boycotted the gathering. Algeria, Oman and Morocco sent
delegations below head-of-state level, making the turnout the
worst in the past four years of Arab League summits.
   Last year's summit in Casablanca, called to address the
Lebanon problem, failed to come up with a workable plan. A
1988 gathering in Algeria was supposed to finance the
Palestinian cause, but Palestine Liberation Organization
leader Yasser Arafat has complained that the funds weren't
forthcoming.
   The Iraqi president opened the Baghdad summit with a
speech attacking Israel. He reiterated his threat of a month
ago that Iraq will use "weapons of total destruction" against
Israel if it attacks Iraq with similar weapons. He blamed the
U.S. for arming and encouraging Israel, saying, "The Zionist
entity would not be able to commit aggression and expansion
territorially at the expense of the Arabs without the
military might and political support of the United States."
   In an interview before the summit, Nizar Hamdoon, Iraq's
deputy foreign minister, said the issue of Soviet immigration
is one on which the Arab position can easily be
misrepresented. "We don't like to appear as if we are against
freedom of movement," he said, but the rights of Soviet Jews
can't be allowed to trample the rights of Palestinians. "We
are for the right of people to move, but we are also for the
right of Palestinians to return to their homes, whether
inside Israel's pre-1967 borders or on the West Bank."
   Mr. Hamdoon said the summit was motivated by fear that the
Middle East could turn more violent in a short time if a
combination of such factors as stagnation in the peace
process, economic hardship in such states as Egypt and Jordan
and the repercussions of Soviet immigration weren't
addressed. "I don't want to talk about months, but there is a
very small gap of time when somebody can do something. After
that it will get out of control," he said.
   Jordan's King Hussein, speaking at the session, asked help
for his state's troubled economy, warning that "abandoning
Jordan is abandoning Palestine." Previously, the king has
said that since 1987 thousands of Palestinians have crossed
the border separating the West Bank from his kingdom, driven
out by Israeli military harassment and fear of extremist West
Bank settlers. If Soviet Jews begin to settle the West Bank
en masse, he says he fears such numbers could accelerate,
destabilizing his already fragile kingdom in which half the
population is Palestinian.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900529-0004
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900529-0004.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Telecommunications Conference Focuses
   On Fiber Optics and Computer Networks
   ----
   By John J. Keller
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/29/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B9B
</SO>
<IN>
COMMUNICATIONS TECHNOLOGY (CMT)
</IN>
<LP>
   STOCKHOLM, Sweden -- The telecommunications industry's
leading technology symposium opened with fiber optic
communications and so-called intelligent computer networks
taking center stage.
   The triennial conference, last held in Phoenix, Ariz., in
1987, goes by the arcane name the International Switching
Symposium. It is a place for the industry's most prominent
scientists and developers to present their views on
leading-edge technologies.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   ISS in the past has offered a window on where the
telecommunications industry is headed in terms of new voice
and data services for business and residential customers.
This year's presentations on optical switches and network
management systems seemed to presage a revolution in the
public phone network over the next three to 10 years.
   These changes will enable companies to begin trading vast
amounts of information with other firms by using fiber optics
and the public network. Moreover, the presentation shows that
public phone companies have begun laying the groundwork for
better integrating of disparate communications technologies,
which include cellular radio and private data networks.
   Many of the technologies discussed were in varying stages
of development at the time of the Phoenix meeting in 1987,
when the thrust of the technical presentations dealt with
so-called System VII common channel signaling networks that
helped route voice and data calls. Others dealt with
Integrated Services Digital Network (ISDN) technology for
sending voice and data calls simultaneously over the same
wire.
   Since Phoenix, System VII networks have proliferated. In
fact, one of those networks figured prominently in the
software malfunction that felled American Telephone &amp;
Telegraph Co.'s long-distance network last January. And ISDN
systems are now being used by numerous companies, such as
American Express Co., to increase the efficiency of their
workers, who can now talk on the phone and share computer
information on their personal computers without having to
make an expensive and time-consuming second call.
   Some of this year's more noteworthy presentations include
those by scientists at AT&amp;T, Japan's NEC Corp. and France's
Alcatel, who are presenting papers on optical computers that
switch voice and data calls using light beams from lasers
rather than electronic signals. Other industry giants, such
as Northern Telecom Ltd. of Canada; Ericsson of Sweden;
Nippon Telegraph and Telephone Corp. of Japan, and British
Telecom plan presentations on high-capacity or broad-band
transmission using fiber optic networks and the methods for
managing such traffic.
   Systems management is becoming more critical because
companies will eventually transmit their data through the
public network at the rate of trillions of bits of
information per second, compared with the millions and in
some cases billions of bits today.
   "In the future, the public networks will have to provide
whatever transmission {pipeline} is needed by a customer and
make it as accessible as dialing a simple voice call," said
Desmond Hudson, president of Northern Telecom World Trade.
   Another focus is so-called Intelligent Networks of
computers that will someday enable phone companies to allow
third-party suppliers, such as software companies, to send
their programs to customers on a dial-up basis. Bell
Communications Research Inc., the laboratory owned by the
seven Bell regionals, and telecommunications authorities from
West Germany, France and Italy are among the presenters in
this category.
   Attendance at this year's ISS underscores the
globalization of the telecommunications industry, with 84
countries sending scientific representatives, compared with
48 countries three years ago.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900529-0003
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900529-0003.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Petroleum Output Is Falling in 3 Nations
   Where Overproduction Led to World Glut
   ----
   By James Tanner
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/29/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C15
</SO>
<CO>
   MDEST
</CO>
<IN>
PETROLEUM (PET)
</IN>
<LP>
   Petroleum output is declining in the three Persian Gulf
nations whose overproduction led to the world oil glut and
the recent sharp fall in prices.
   That is the new assessment by several leading monitors of
OPEC production. They will be reporting estimates that total
production in May by the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries is down as much as 500,000 barrels a day or more
from the level in April.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Such a production trend, if it holds, could have a major
impact on world oil markets by providing support to weak
prices. It was the apparent lack of follow-up to OPEC's early
May pledge to trim high output that led to the price drop of
more than $2 a barrel.
   The new May estimates are only preliminary and could prove
to be misleading signals for oil markets. Still, they should
provide OPEC with some breathing room and shrink prospects of
a runaway output race.
   The estimates differ some on how much OPEC is producing.
But it is agreed the major reduction so far is by Saudi
Arabia -- which appears to be producing slightly under its
quota of 5.4 million barrels a day -- and that there are
signs of modest cuts in both Kuwait and the United Arab
Emirates, the chronic overproducers.
   "It's not out of the question for Kuwait, which has cut
back spot sales to U.S. customers significantly, to be down
200,000 barrels a day for the month to around 1.7 million,"
said Cristina Haus, who monitors OPEC production for Energy
Security Analysis, a Washington-based company that tracks oil
supplies world-wide.
   As a result, she has lowered the output figure she expects
to report for OPEC for May from a prior estimate of 23.5
million barrels a day. Now, she said, OPEC's May production
appears to be 23 million to 23.5 million barrels a day, down
from 23.7 million in April and more than 24 million in March.
   Some other monitors of OPEC production see May output
settling in a higher range of 23.4 million to 23.5 million
barrels a day. But that still would mean a drop of 500,000
barrels a day because they have revised upward their old
April estimates to some 24 million.
   "If we see another decline of 500,000 barrels a day in
June, that will be the one million total they were looking
for," said a European-based monitor of OPEC production.
Although the exporters had stated after their early May
meeting that they planned to reduce OPEC output a total of
1.4 million barrels a day through July, several leading oil
ministers had suggested privately that they believed oil
markets would be satisfied with a drop of one million.
   But even though the new production indications for May
could be a firming factor for oil prices, they still don't
end a major worry for many members of OPEC. Neither Kuwait
nor the United Arab Emirates will have yet met in full
reduction promises of 400,000 barrels a day and 200,000
barrels a day, respectively. The concern is that Saudi Arabia
will retaliate by raising its output back to 5.7 million
barrels a day.
   "If you take the May figures at face value," said a senior
OPEC official, "only the Saudis are down significantly. The
issue is how long they will stay down."
   Only last week, the kingdom may have signaled that its
patience was wearing thin. In an official government
statement, Hisham M. Nazer, the Saudi oil minister,
reiterated the kingdom's commitment to the early May accord,
noting that it had given its "word of honor" to market no
more oil than its official quota. He called on other OPEC
members to practice a similar production discipline.
   Still, the authoritative Middle East Economic Survey,
which has close contacts with the kingdom, reported yesterday
that "the Saudis aren't now planning to take any steps to
review their present {production} policy until around
mid-June."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900529-0002
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900529-0002.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Shearson Picks
   Linen to Head
   Brokerage Unit
   ----
   By William Power
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/29/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C1
</SO>
<CO>
   AXP SLH WNEWS
</CO>
<IN>
SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- American Express Co., in a move that confirms
plans to split Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in half, is
expected to put one of its top travel executives in charge of
Shearson's vast brokerage and money-management side.
   The executive, Jonathan S. Linen, is currently head of the
traveler's checks, direct marketing and publishing group of
American Express Travel Related Services Co. Described by
colleagues as "very refined" and statesmanlike, Mr. Linen has
no experience running a brokerage firm, let alone one of
Shearson's size.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Yet despite his inexperience on Wall Street, the
46-year-old Mr. Linen is considered one of American Express's
rising stars, with experience at fixing the firm's troubled
businesses over the years. "He's big on customer service and
quality. Those things are important {too,}" said one American
Express person familiar with the situation who requested
anonymity.
   When he takes over at Shearson this week -- an official
announcement is expected today -- Mr. Linen will run the
nation's second-biggest brokerage firm behind Merrill Lynch &amp;
Co., with 470 branches, nearly 10,000 brokers and $90 billion
under management.
   His job will be to restore the brokerage force's shattered
morale, stem defections of key personnel and preside over the
cleanup of Shearson stumbles -- including its spotty record
in marketing limited-partnership investments during the
1980s.
   Neither American Express nor Shearson would comment about
the expected naming of Mr. Linen. However, it's understood
that the appointment has been in the works for most of this
month, and was completed over the holiday weekend.
   The loser in the management move is Hardwick Simmons, for
nearly a decade the head of Shearson's individual-investor
businesses, including the brokerage network. Mr. Simmons
resigned Friday after being told he was being passed over in
favor of Mr. Linen. Mr. Simmons couldn't be reached for
comment over the weekend.
   The expected heads of the non-brokerage side of the
reconfigured Shearson are expected to come from within
Shearson. The betting is that Richard S. Fuld Jr. and Sherman
Lewis will co-head this side of the firm, which will operate
under the resurrected name of Lehman Brothers, and will
include Shearson's investment banking and trading operations.
Shearson took over the venerable Lehman Brothers Kuhn Loeb
Inc. investment bank in 1984.
   Mr. Linen's side of the firm will probably retain the
Shearson name, and be called Shearson Group or something
similar.
   American Express -- forced to pump more than $1 billion
into struggling Shearson and acquire the remaining common
stock it doesn't already own -- has been moving to put its
imprint on the company and restore confidence in it. The
Shearson split-up is part of that plan; American Express
denies Shearson is being divided as a precursor to a sale of
one or both parts of the firm.
   Earlier in the year, Shearson Chairman Peter Cohen was
ousted and was replaced by Howard Clark Jr., at the time
American Express chief financial officer.
   Now, Mr. Clark's friend Mr. Linen is moving down from
American Express's executive suite to Shearson's. A person
familiar with the thinking of James D. Robinson III, American
Express chairman, avows that Mr. Robinson has "gone to the
A-team" in installing Mr. Linen at Shearson.
   "It's Jim's reaffirmation that he's serious about reviving
Shearson," the person said.
   Mr. Linen's first job at American Express 20 years ago was
as an assistant to Howard Clark Sr., then-chairman of
American Express and father of the current Shearson chairman.
   American Express has shown a clear dissatisfaction with
the management talent currently at Shearson. It brought in
its own man, Mr. Clark, to run Shearson after Mr. Cohen's
departure. Now, it again has tapped an American Express man
for a senior management role at Shearson, bypassing Shearson
hopefuls.
   American Express executives say privately that they think
Shearson can turn around if it's run as well as American
Express is.
   Still, American Express has had problems of its own over
the years. And Mr. Linen has been the man that Mr. Robinson
has turned to in the past for problem-solving. Among other
things, Mr. Linen has handled potential major problems at
American Express's travel, publishing and insurance
businesses, say American Express executives.
   Mr. Linen wasn't available for comment yesterday.
   Mr. Linen's new move will cause some shuffling at American
Express Travel Related Services, where he was one of three
chief executives who, along with Chairman Aldo Papone, report
directly to Mr. Robinson.
   Mr. Linen had been head of what is technically called the
Direct Marketing and Travelers Cheques Group, encompassing
traveler's checks, publishing, merchandise services,
world-wide quality assurance, the Amex Life insurance arm and
investment products.
   It is expected that Mr. Linen's responsibilities will be
divided between Edwin Cooperman, chief executive of Travel
Related Services North America (which includes American
Express charge cards), and Rick Thoman, chief executive of
American Express International.
   Although one American Express executive denied it
yesterday, Mr. Linen's shift to Shearson could remove him as
a candidate to succeed Mr. Robinson as American Express
chairman one day.
   In April 1989, when American Express reorganized top
management, the company indicated that one of the three chief
executives in Travel Related Services would probably be named
to follow Mr. Robinson. A job at Shearson, never considered a
direct member of the American Express family, seems to take
Mr. Linen out of the running for the top job, even if he were
to be successful in helping to revive the brokerage firm.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900529-0001
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900529-0001.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Tudor Investment's Jones Pleads Guilty
   To Filling Protected Maryland Wetlands
   ----
   By Milo Geyelin
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/29/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B5
</SO>
<IN>
ENVIRONMENT (ENV)
</IN>
<GV>
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)
</GV>
<LP>
   Paul Tudor Jones II, one of the country's most successful
futures and options traders, pleaded guilty to a federal
charge of illegally filling protected wetlands on Maryland's
Eastern Shore.
   The guilty plea, unsealed Friday along with a seven-count
indictment against a project manager hired by Mr. Jones, is
the largest case ever prosecuted criminally by federal
officials for illegally filling wetlands.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Mr. Jones, 35 years old, is the founder and president of
Tudor Investment Corp., one of the most closely watched
trading firms on Wall Street. He pleaded guilty to a
one-count misdemeanor that carries a maximum jail sentence of
six months and agreed to $2 million in fines and restitution.
The charges stem from plans by Tudor to build a corporate
retreat and wildlife habitat -- Tudor Farms -- in Dorchester
County, Md.
   The indictment and the guilty plea were unsealed by the
U.S. attorney's office in Baltimore, which spent a year
investigating the case. "The filing of today's charges
reflects the seriousness with which this office and federal
law enforcement in Maryland view environmental crime," said
Breckenridge L. Wilcox, U.S. attorney in Maryland. "The
protection of Maryland's Chesapeake Bay wetlands is of vital
importance in the effort to arrest the Bay's decline . . ."
   Mr. Jones, emphasizing that the plea agreement will have
no impact on his company's investment operations, said that
Tudor Farms had been conceived as a conservation project and
that the firm retained 15 experts, including a project
manager, William B. Ellen.
   "We believed in error that our experts had properly
addressed the complex issues related to habitat development
in wetlands . . .," Mr. Jones said in a statement. "The
severe drought in 1988 . . . made it difficult to recognize
non-tidal wetlands. With identification so difficult, certain
permits to move soil on these wetlands were not obtained."
   Neither Mr. Jones nor his attorney could be reached for
comment.
   According to a copy of the plea agreement, Mr. Jones hired
Mr. Ellen to develop a corporate retreat for duck hunting on
3,272 acres of prime shore land that Mr. Jones bought between
1987 and 1989. More than half the land was marsh, and Mr.
Ellen was contracted to clear wooded areas, dig ponds, build
roads and fill in tidal areas with gravel.
   Federal prosecutors allege that Mr. Ellen filled in 86
acres of wetlands without a permit, despite an order to cease
and desist from the Army Corps of Engineers in February 1988.
Copies of the order were mailed to Mr. Ellen and Mr. Jones,
according to Mr. Jones's plea agreement, yet the work
continued unabated. Mr. Jones visited the site an average of
twice a month, according to federal prosecutors, but it
remains unclear whether he was aware of any problem over
proper permitting.
   According to his plea agreement, Mr. Ellen refused to stop
work and the project was only halted after the Corps of
Engineers contacted the independent contractors involved. Mr.
Jones expressed "surprise and dismay" when told the extent of
the damage in March 1989 and immediately fired Mr. Ellen.
   Since then, according to the plea agreement, he has
"cooperated fully" with plans to restore the land. Mr. Jones
agreed to pay a $1 million fine, another $1 million in
restitution and restore the damage done on his land.
   Mr. Ellen, of Matthews, Va., could not be reached for
comment. He was charged with six counts of knowingly
violating the Clean Water Act by filling in wetlands, and one
count of violating the Rivers and Harbors Act by dumping fill
material in navigable water. He faces a maximum 31-year
prison term and more than $1.5 million in fines.
</TEXT>
